{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"86d755f0-3bf1-4d33-b4bd-403a07a45d18","content":"Here are the five issues you'll hit upgrading to .NET 10:\n\n**1. InlineArray + explicit StructLayout → `TypeLoadException`**\n.NET 10 disallows explicit layout on inline array types. Remove `[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]` — the runtime manages inline array layout automatically.\n\n**2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux returns different values**\n.NET 10 changed the Linux implementation to return the actual filesystem type name (e.g., `\"ext4\"`, `\"tmpfs\"`). Verify your string comparisons match the new return values.\n\n**3. NU1510 warnings (pruned dependencies)**\n.NET 10 enables dependency pruning by default. NU1510 warns when packages are pruned because they're already provided by the shared framework. Remove those now-unnecessary explicit `<PackageReference>` entries, or suppress with `<SuppressTfmDependencyPruning>true</SuppressTfmDependencyPruning>` if needed temporarily.\n\n**4. Transitive NuGet audit warnings**\n.NET 10 defaults `<NuGetAuditMode>` to `all` (previously `direct`). You'll now see vulnerability warnings for transitive packages. Update vulnerable transitive dependencies (pin versions via `<PackageReference Include=\"...\" VersionOverride=\"...\" />`), or use central package management to control them.\n\n**5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` no longer returns null**\n`Stem` is now non-nullable and returns `string.Empty` instead of `null`. Change:\n```csharp\n// Before\nif (match.Stem == null)\n\n// After\nif (string.IsNullOrEmpty(match.Stem))\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"19934db3-798b-414e-b72e-bcbe10e92399","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about issues they'll encounter when upgrading a .NET 9 class library to .NET 10. Let me address each of the five points they've raised, based on my knowledge of .NET 10 breaking changes and new features.\n\n1. **[InlineArray(16)] struct with explicit [StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]** - In .NET 10, there's a breaking change where inline arrays now must not have explicit layout attributes. The runtime will throw a `TypeLoadException` if an inline array has `[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit)]`. The fix is to remove the explicit `StructLayout` attribute and let the runtime manage the layout.\n\n\n2. **DriveInfo.DriveFormat on Linux** - In .NET 10, `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux now returns the actual filesystem type string (like \"ext4\" or \"xfs\") instead of the previous behavior, which was less consistent. This is a breaking change if your code was relying on the old return values. I'm realizing the actual breaking change is that `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux now consistently returns the filesystem type string (like \"ext4\" or \"btrfs\"), but the user needs to verify their string comparisons still work with whatever values are actually being returned in .NET 10.\n\nThere's also a new NuGet feature in .NET 10 called dependency pruning that's enabled by default, which generates NU1510 warnings when transitive dependencies are already satisfied by the framework—the fix is to either suppress these warnings or remove redundant package references that are already provided by the framework.\n\nFor the fourth point, NuGet audit has expanded in .NET 10 to check transitive dependencies for vulnerabilities by default, whereas in earlier versions it only audited direct dependencies.  You can either fix the vulnerabilities or revert to the old behavior by setting `NuGetAuditMode` to `direct`, though that's not recommended.\n\nFor the fifth point, `FilePatternMatch.Stem` is now non-nullable in .NET 10 and returns `string.Empty` instead of `null` when there's no stem, so any null checks against it are now dead code that should be replaced with checks for empty strings.","outputTokens":1784,"requestId":"9840:931B0:11A972:165130:69F54EAF"},"id":"9aed6b90-0370-4265-99d8-8382f0b60c60","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:09:36.276Z","par